This paper is likely to belong to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category as it focuses on designing a self-exploratory reinforcement learning framework for the base station to choose a suitable modulation and coding scheme that maximizes spectral efficiency in 5G networks. Additionally, the paper also discusses the channel quality indicator reported by the user equipment, which is a key aspect of network communication. 

The paper also involves the use of machine learning algorithms, specifically Q-learning, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. 

Furthermore, the paper discusses information theory and the transmission of data, which could place it in the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. 

The use of reinforcement learning to optimize network performance also suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper involves the use of artificial intelligence techniques to optimize network performance, which could place it in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category.
